ElementDescription: The NDAR Global Unique Identifier (GUID) for research subject
Subject ID how it's defined in lab/project
Date on which the interview/genetic test/sampling/imaging/biospecimen was completed. MM/DD/YYYY
Age in months at the time of the interview/test/sampling/imaging.
Notes: Age is rounded to chronological month. If the research participant is 15-days-old at time of interview, the appropriate value would be 0 months. If the participant is 16-days-old, the value would be 1 month.
M = Male; F = Female; O=Other; NR = Not reported

ElementDescription: Do you use any online social networking sites; such as Facebook; Instagram; Twitter; or Snapchat?
If yes; how many sites do you use?
Notes: 1=One; 2=Two to Four; 3=Five to Ten; 4=More than Ten

ElementDescription: Do you use these sites to directly communicate with friends and family?
On average; how many days per week do you use these sites to communicate with friends and family (not including time spent browsing pictures or reading posts)?
Notes: 1=One day; 2=Two to Three days; 3=Four to Six days; 4=Daily

ElementDescription: On days that you use these sites; how many minutes per day do you use them to communicate with friends and family (not including time spent browsing pictures or reading posts)?
Notes: 1=One to Ten minutes; 2=Ten to Thirty minutes; 3=Thirty minutes to one Hour; 4=One hour to Two hours; 5=More than Two hours

ElementDescription: How important are these sites to maintaining communication with your friends and family?
Of the people you communicate with online; how many would you be comfortable discussing private matters?
Notes: 1=Zero; 2=One to Two; 3=Three to five; 4=Six to 10; 5=More than 10

ElementDescription: Of the people you communicate with online; how many do you feel close to such that you could call on them for help?
Notes: 1=Zero; 2=One to Two; 3=Three to five; 4=Six to 10; 5=More than 10

ElementDescription: Considering the pattern of interaction with your friends that you just described to me; since what age has it been like this?
